\noindent For a surd $r=a + b \sqrt{c}$, its conjugate is defined as $r^*=a - b \sqrt{c}$.\\
This means that 
$$r \cdot  r^* = \left(a+b \sqrt{c}\right)\left(a-b \sqrt{c}\right)$$
$$\left(a+b \sqrt{c}\right)\left(a-b \sqrt{c}\right) \equiv  a^2 - b^2c$$\\
This is the same for complex numbers, which are defined as $z=a+bi$.\\
If $z=a+bi$ then $z^*=a-bi$. This means that: 
$$z\cdot z^* \equiv  a^2 - b^2i^2$$ 
However, since, by definition, $i^2 \equiv  -1$, we can simplify this to 
$$z\cdot z^* \equiv  a^2 + b^2$$
